  "caseStudy_eyebrow": "Case study",
  "caseStudy_title": "Cosmos on Canvas —",
  "caseStudy_titleAccent": "Custom Painters at 60 fps.",
  "caseStudy_subtitle": "The background of this landing is not an image or Lottie — it is 7 types of celestial bodies painted in real time via CustomPainter. Over 140 draw calls per frame, seed-deterministic, all derived from a single tick.",
  "caseStudy_ctaExplore": "Explore the full case study",
  "caseStudy_pivotEyebrow": "WHY PAINT",
  "caseStudy_pivotTitle": "Canvas beats assets when geometry is parameterizable.",
  "caseStudy_pivotPara1": "Planet images would be static — fixed size, fixed color, no orbit animation or drift. Lottie would solve animation but add a dependency, bundle weight and limit variations. CustomPainter takes parameters (palette, surface pattern, radius, seed) and draws live — each planet is unique without costing an extra asset.",
  "caseStudy_pivotPara2": "The CosmosPainter renders 7 body types: planets (with rings and moons), nebulae, spiral galaxies, pulsars, asteroid belts, gas wisps and comets with a time window. A single AnimationController feeds the tick [0..1] that derives all animations — orbits, pulses, drifts — with no parallel timers or state machines.",
  "caseStudy_pivotPara3": "Each planet goes through 6 paint layers: bloom (outer glow), atmospheric rim, solid body with gradient, surface pattern (bands, speckled or hemispheres), terminator (3D shadow) and highlight. The result is a neon planet in ~15 draw calls running at 60 fps on web and mobile.",
  "caseStudy_recoveryLabel": "COSMOS · LIVE",
  "caseStudy_recoveryHint": "What you see above is being painted in real time.\nNo image, no static asset.",
  "caseStudy_painterStrainTitle": "Planet in 6 layers",
  "caseStudy_painterStrainCaption": "Bloom → rim → body → surface → terminator → highlight. Each layer is a RadialGradient positioned with canvas.clipPath isolating the geometry. 5-color palette interpolated automatically.",
  "caseStudy_painterTempoTitle": "Spiral galaxy",
  "caseStudy_painterTempoCaption": "Arms in logarithmic spiral with up to 320 dust particles. drawPoints() groups them into 3 GPU calls by size tier — 100x less overhead than individual drawCircle.",
  "caseStudy_painterPeriodTitle": "Named constellations",
  "caseStudy_painterPeriodCaption": "Southern Cross, Orion and Triangulum Australe with pulsating stars and edges connecting pairs. AnimationController via super(repaint:) — the engine skips build/layout, paints directly.",
  "caseStudy_decisionArchEyebrow": "RENDERING",
  "caseStudy_decisionArchTitle": "super(repaint:) instead of AnimatedBuilder",
  "caseStudy_decisionArchBody": "The AnimationController is passed directly to the CustomPainter via super(repaint:). Flutter's engine skips the build and layout phases of the pipeline and goes straight to paint on each tick. In scenes with 140+ draw calls, this saving eliminates unnecessary widget rebuilds every 16ms.",
  "caseStudy_decisionPaintersEyebrow": "DETERMINISM",
  "caseStudy_decisionPaintersTitle": "Seed-based: same input, same scene",
  "caseStudy_decisionPaintersBody": "Every stochastic position — planet spots, asteroid positions, drift phases — uses Random(seed). The cosmos is reproducible: same seed, same scene on any platform, any restart. Enables deterministic visual testing and consistent screenshots.",
  "caseStudy_decisionStateEyebrow": "BATCH",
  "caseStudy_decisionStateTitle": "drawPoints() for density without cost",
  "caseStudy_decisionStateBody": "Spiral galaxies and asteroid belts use drawPoints(PointMode.points, offsets, paint) to render hundreds of particles in 1-3 GPU calls. The naive approach (one drawCircle per particle) would cost 320 calls. Batching is what makes dense scenes viable at 60 fps.",
  "caseStudy_takeawayEyebrow": "TAKEAWAY",
  "caseStudy_takeawayTitle": "The cosmos you see on this page is code — not an asset, not a capture, not an external library.",
  "caseStudy_takeawayBody": "It is ~1200 LOC of pure painter, with no dependency outside the Flutter SDK. Paint reused as a field, shouldRepaint comparing properties, canvas.save/restore around each transform. The same painter renders the landing hero and can be reused on any app screen with different parameters.",

